block.p: The Federal National Mortgage Association, also known as Fannie Mae, priced a total of $1.3 billion yesterday in 5-year and 10-year debentures at par through various securities dealers.

For $800 million of 6.05 percent debentures due 1997, the yield will be about 23 basis points more than Treasury securities with a similar maturity. These securities, underwriters said, would be redeemable on or after Oct. 27, 1995, with the first interest payment on April 27, 1993.
The Federal National Mortgage Association, also known as Fannie Mae, priced a total of $1.3 billion yesterday in 5-year and 10-year debentures at par through various securities dealers.

For $800 million of 6.05 percent debentures due 1997, the yield will be about 23 basis points more than Treasury securities with a similar maturity. These securities, underwriters said, would be redeemable on or after Oct. 27, 1995, with the first interest payment on April 27, 1993.
The $500 million of 10-year 7.30 percent debentures yield about 55 basis points above comparable Treasuries and are redeemable on or after Oct. 28, 1997.
Underwriters said Fannie Mae had the option to redeem all or part of both issues.
